er, is not simply to condemn Heidegger but rather to invite us to think something to which the thinker of being remained blind: anti-Semitism as a self-hatred haunting the history of the West—and of Christianity in its drive toward an auto-foundation that would leave behind its origins in Judaism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAntisemitismxPhilosophy. 0aAntisemitismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aAntisemitism--Germany--History--20th century. 4aJewish Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aBlack Notebooks.  aChristianity.  aHeidegger.  aWestern Culture.  aanti-Semitism.  abeing.  ahistory of being.  ametaphysics.  aphilosophy.1 aFort, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFort, Jeff.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823275953zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823275953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823275953/original  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK